## Fiume

Fiume which is now called Rijeka (both words mean river) is a port on the East side of
the Northern Adriatic. Frequent changes of sovereignty make its postal history of exceptional interest. (The stamps now are mostly collected with [Croatia](../croatia/Introduction)).

In the middle of the fifteenth century it was bought by the Emperor Frederick III and was under Austrian rule. It was temporarily occupied by Venice during the war of League of Cambrai and possibly at other times. At the end of the second decade of the eighteenth century Charles V made it a free port. In 1776 Maria Theresa joined it to the Croatian Crownland, only to declare it three years later, after receiving complaints, a \textit{corpus separatum} of the Hungarian crown. The inhabitants of Fiume were hostile to the Croats and they helped maintain their independence by allyng themselves with their neighbour next but one. 

Between 1809 and 1813 the area was under Napoleon's control and became part of the Province of Illyria. In 1813 the English occupied the town. They left no trace of any mails.

